The stability of CZS and CZS/CDs/BWO–2 was evaluated and compared (Fig. 3
                           g). It is distinct that neat CZS suffers from the weak photo-stability with an appreciable shrinkage of activity (39.4%) at the fifth recycling run, primarily arising from the severe photo-corrosion of CZS. Excitingly, CZS/CDs/BWO–2 manifests the steady-state degradation efficiency of TC over five cycles of reuse. Furthermore, the recycled CZS/CDs/BWO–2 displays no evident change of the phases and microstructure (
                              Fig. S2
                           ) compared with those of the fresh one, further verifying the high durability and sustainability of CZS/CDs/BWO–2 material for wastewater decontamination. The main reason for the stability improvement is that after integration with CDs/BWO, the photo-created h+ in CZS is readily recombined with e– coming from BWO, therefore contributing to the durability enhancement of the ternary heterojunction [22]. Furthermore, the concentrations of the leaching of toxic metal ions (Cd and Zn) during the cycling reaction in CZS/CDs/BWO-2 system were determined by flame atomic absorption spectrometry (
                              Fig. S3
                           ). Apparently, the concentrations of leached Cd and Zn at different initial pH were lower than the national emission standards, suggesting the inevitable metal leaching does not cause secondary pollution. These findings reveal that creating CZS/CDs/BWO S-scheme heterojunction is a favorable route to simultaneously warrant the elevated photo-activity and stability of CZS.

The BET surface areas of BWO, CZS, CZS/BWO, and CZS/CDs/BWO–2 were assessed by N2 adsorption−desorption measurements (
                           Fig. S6
                        ) [61–65]. Clearly, all the isotherms coincide well with the type-IV isotherm, signifying the presence of meso/macro-pore in these samples. Evidently, CZS/CDs/BWO–2 owns notably higher surface area (54.7 m2 g−1) than BWO (19.2 m2 g−1), CZS (25.9 m2 g−1), CZS/BWO (40.7 m2 g−1), which favors the effective photo-degradation process [66].
